ies of six novels (by Aravind Adiga, Margaret Atwood, Sebastian Barry, Mark Haddon, DBC Pierre, Zadie Smith) and their attention profiles, this work describes the Booker as a 'problem-driven attention-generating mechanism', the influence of which can only be understood in relation to other participants in literary interaction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBooker PrizexHistory. 0aEnglish fictionzGreat Britainy21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterary prizeszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aMass media and literaturezGreat Britain. 4aBook Market. 4aBritish Studies. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFiction. 4aGeneral Literature Studies. 4aLiterary Prize. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aLiterature. 4aReviewing. 4aSociology of Art. 4aUnited Kingdom. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBook Market.  aBritish Studies.  aCultural Studies.  aFiction.  aGeneral Literature Studies.  aLiterary Prize.  aLiterary Studies.  aLiterature.  aReviewing.  aSociology of Art.  aUnited Kingdom.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruyterttranscript English Contemporary eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311066154540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783839438534zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783839438534423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783839438534/original  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBO